I did that also when I was a kid with my toys and my own adventures. I dont feel it cheapens what happened in the original trilogy i feel like it honors it and brings reverence to it. But I dont because I remember what made me fall in love with these cheesy little movies. I think we have forgotten that now we say why didnt they just leave it alone. Yet we all wanted them to continue the story. We forget that by the time they decided to start 7,8,9 our characters have aged and cant be central leads anymore. Let me say a few other things that I further proves my generation the Gen xers really have become cynical.  I still really know nothing about boba fett. Not with out researching or reading things outside of movies. I mean I know he is a clone, I know he is a bounty hunter. And I know when I was a kid he was Cool. I know nothing about those whole bounty hunters on the deck in empire IG 88, Bosk , Dengar . What do we really know about Jabba from the movies other than he is a vile gangster. What do we know about the sajd people. Hell what do we really know about Yoda. So I dont need more about Knights of Ren. The movie isnt the Knights of Ren  anymore than empire or return were the story of Boba Fett or Jaba. I didnt need to know all that to take away from my movie experience. I enjoyed the movie I made a connection with it. For me It made the whole 9 movies connect to me and my inner child. I dont want to go to movies and worry about what it didnt give me i want to go to movies and enjoy what they do give me. And hopefully I enjoy it. If i dont i wont watch it again.  I know this there was a time in my late 20's and early thirties my dear mother asked me do you not like star wars anymore. Because i didnt care to watch them like i did. I told her I did at the time I just have watched it so much. I thought about that after watching this movie today for the third time this weekend. I didnt like them because at that age I was cynical and thought they were childish and cheesy. But now I look at it and realize I do love star wars all of it that entire galaxy far far away that happened long ago. And I cant get enough of it.  Are some movies better than others of course. Are some not as bad as people think yes. I enjoyed Solo did I need it probably not am I glad I watched yes. Do I like rogue one yes did I need it no but I love it. Do I need the Mandalorian no am I glad I have it absolutely.  Did I need episodes 7-9 no but I'm glad I got it and I'm glad I saw it. Last thing I personally love Rey taking Skywalker name again it's a sign of reverence and honor to Anakin to Luke to Leigha to Ben. I think people forget with this whole it cheapens vader sacrifice.  It doesnt the sacrifice isnt about if the emperor survived or not. Its about saving his son and redemption for him being the man he should have been before the fall. Have a nice day. And when I was a kid I wanted to be a Skywalker so for old times sake. May the force be with you always

snippet.textDisplay: When it comes to a trilogy, you have to have the same writer(s). You can bring on different directors to collaborate with in order to spice up the story and visual style but character arcs and a cohesive narrative need to be established before the cameras start rolling on the first installment. Personally, I infinitely prefer Rian Johnson's vision. JJ seemed to wing it both times in terms of telling a story. He set up the characters very well in The Force Awakens and he had all kinds of paths to go down in terms of story but chose the more derivative route. With The Rise of Skywalker he just steered the ship into the direction he ideally would've gone down if he did Episode VIII. Here's the thing; once signed onto Episode IX, JJ had to let go of any bitterness he held towards the decisions made in The Last Jedi. If he wanted to do VIII, STAY ON FOR VIII. Don't subtly retcon the one film in the middle you didn't do because you weren't a fan of what someone else decided to do with the characters you introduced. Take what Johnson did and run with it. This was a 3 hour movie crammed into 2 hours and 20 minutes. There was potential and most of it was squandered because THERE WAS NO VISION. Lucasfilm just played a really fucked up game of hot potato! I'm now wondering how Colin Trevorrow's Episode IX would've unfolded. And we'll probably never know.

snippet.textDisplay: The OT didn't really have a plan, either - I think that's my main gripe with the fallback of "there was no plan, and it shows" when it comes to criticism of this trilogy. Well, yes, that's true (picture the insanity of a Trevorrow ending!), but that's also true of the OT once the nostalgia goggles come off, and even with Lucas revisionist edits at play, it still really, really shows between films, and the only reason we don't all pick at it more is that we're all under forty, and have grown up with them intact all our lives. The canon has become ingrained into pop culture and film history over time.  The only one that appeared to have even a vague roadmap was, weirdly, the prequel trilogy - and heaven knows I'm not enjoying elevating THAT one above these (better) two.
